# How to Run the Animations

All animations in this repository are built using **Manim**.

---

## 1. Clone the Repository

```bash
git clone https://github.com/Fortnight-wow/Visual-Mathematics-of-Finance.git

cd Visual-Mathematics-of-Finance
```

---

## 2. Install Dependencies

Install all required packages:

```bash
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

or manually:

```bash
pip install manim numpy
```

---

## 3. Render an Animation

The general format is:

```bash
manim [quality] animations/<file_name>.py <SceneName>
```

Example:

```bash
manim -pqh animations/brownian_motion.py BrownianMotion
```

---

## Quality Options

| Flag | Quality |
|--------|----------|
| `-pql` | Low Quality (Fast) |
| `-pqm` | Medium Quality |
| `-pqh` | High Quality |
| `-pqk` | 4K Quality |

Example:

```bash
manim -pqk animations/geometric_brownian_motion.py GeometricBrownianMotion
```

---

## Available Animations

### Brownian Motion

```bash
manim -pqh animations/brownian_motion.py BrownianMotion
```

### Geometric Brownian Motion

```bash
manim -pqh animations/geometric_brownian_motion.py GeometricBrownianMotion
```

### Ito's Lemma

```bash
manim -pqh animations/ito_lemma.py ItoLemma
```

### Black-Scholes PDE

```bash
manim -pqh animations/black_scholes_pde.py BlackScholesPDE
```

### Delta Hedging

```bash
manim -pqh animations/delta_hedging.py DeltaHedging
```

---

## Output Location

Rendered videos are automatically saved by Manim inside:

```text
media/
└── videos/
```

The exact path depends on the quality selected.

---

## Recommended Learning Order

If you are new to quantitative finance, watch the animations in this order:

1. Brownian Motion
2. Geometric Brownian Motion
3. Ito's Lemma
4. Black-Scholes PDE
5. Delta Hedging

This follows the same progression used in many quantitative finance courses.